UI Mini-Project

UI Case Study

an exploration by massimo mangiola

Humans are, sad to say, very sensitive creatures. We injure and get sick very easily, and the repricussions can stick with us for our lifetimes. This makes it very hard to design an application that's intuitive to use for anyone on the planet: some are blind, some have difficulty moving, and so on. The reality is that most apps simply aren't usable for some people. What's worse is that these populations are the ones who would benefit most from technology.

Battle Plan

I'll make a mobile app specifically designed for people suffering from disabilities to manage their health. The two most important features: reminders to take medications and planning for doctor appointments. It would be nice to be able to create general reminders as well.

User Research

As this application is to be used by people suffering with chronic health conditions, it is paramount to design an interface that is as inclusive as possible. I must take into account as many disabilities as I can; this is the area that will be targeted with my research and surveys. A list of common disabilities within are user population will be created, and each condition will be assigned a priority based on how common it is. Such a survey could look like the following:

The answers to these questions will be used to guide our priorities for an upcoming medical app. Feel free to skip any question if you are uncomfortable answering.


  1. Do you suffer from any chronic illness?
  2. If so, which one(s)?
  3. If applicable, how does your condition impact the way you use software or websites?
  4. If you take medications, do you forget to take them occasionally?
  5. How do you keep track of upcoming doctor appointments?
  6. Would you use a mobile app that keeps track of your medications and appointments?
  7. If so, is there anything you absolutely must have in such an app?
  8. What is your sex and age?

Research Results

Based on user responses, I would be able to hone in on which specific disabilities we should be targeting. I don't have any actual results from such a population, so I'll use statistics from Statistics Canada (source):

Condition Type Percent of Population
Pain 16.7%
Flexibility 10.9%
Mobility 10.6%
Mental health 10.4%
Seeing 7.4%
Hearing 5.6%
Learning 5.6%
Dexterity 5.0%
Memory 4.9%
Population Disability Percentage
Senior women 41.8%
Senior men 38.9%
Middle-aged women 26.9%
Young women 24.7%
Middle-aged men 21.1%
Young men 15.8%

From this data, I can determine that pain and movement-related conditions should be prioritized. This could translate to minimizing the required amount of inputs our users need to give. In addition, I should also assume that women will be a significant portion of our user base. This doesn't necessarily impact as much as the disabilities, but it's important to keep in mind. My personas will reflect the statistics accordingly.

User Personas

I'll make some fictional characters that represent the main user base. This will help give a clearer picture of how people will be using the app.

User Journey

It's helpful to have a diagram of how a typical user will interact with the app. Here's one for my previous user persona, Jessica:

This is useful for discovering potential negative interactions; I can plan on mitigating them before even writing a single line of code. For example, I now know that I should make the reminder editing process very quick and seamless to avoid it being cumbersome.

Wireframe

Keeping the personas in mind, I create a very basic wireframe of the app:

This design is as simple and easy to understand as can be. The home page shows you an overview of your reminders and meds. Then, there's a page for each main feature of the app (general reminders, medication routine, and appointments). Each page is easily accessible from large buttons on the bottom of the screen. No dropdown menus or anything hidden.

Prototype

After making some rough drafts, I'm free to start work on the final version. Firstly, I choose a color palette that's appropriate; a more clean, "clinical" selection makes sense here. Gray backgrounds with green accents, and a hint of red for portraying negative elements like overdue reminders. After making an app icon, we arrive on the home page:

Each basic function of the app has its own page, accessible via the bottom menu. As flexibility and dexterity are huge points of contention for some users, they are accessible with one hand with the thumbs (if you're holding the phone in your palm). Fonts are clear and readable, which is important for anyone with a sight disability.

Here's what each page looks like:

In order to add reminders or appointments, a button exists on each page. Tapping it enables an edit mode that can be toggled on and off, like so:

Usability Testing

Making users actually test the application is crucial for any software, but in this scenario it's essential. As I'm dealing with people that may have physical restraints, there's no way of knowing how they may be hindered beforehand. Maybe there's a certain element of my design that, while being created in good intentions, is actually counter-productive. An example of this would be the bottom navigation menu. It was made with the assumption that the user will hold the phone in their hand, but this isn't always the case. Testing would reveal whether or not it would be better to place it elsewhere.

Here's a decent test suite that we could ask testers to complete. After they complete the actions, I would record their feedback and see if there are common complaints.

Please complete the following actions on our testing application.


  1. View your current reminders.
  2. Create a new reminder.
  3. Mark a reminder as complete.
  4. Delete a reminder.
  5. View your medication routine.
  6. Create a new medication routine.
  7. Mark a medication as taken for the day.
  8. Create a new doctor's appointment.

Please list any troubles you had, or features you wish were easier.

Note how there's a lack of quantitative information: no "rate on a scale of 1 to 10" questions. This is intentional; disabilities are highly personal, and direct participant feedback (their words) is much more valuable than a number. I need to know how their specific ability impacts that specific user, and make changes if necessary.

Reflecting

This study highlights a fundamental issue that every designer must face: you are creating an app for people who work completely different from you. This is always the case, disability or not, but it's much clearer here.

I wasn't able to actually get feedback from our main population, but asking friends and family led to some common responses: elements on the screen are very large. While this was intentional as to help visually impaired users, it was perhaps too heavily leaned upon. After all, initial research showed that visual disabilities actually rank quite a bit lower than the others. And like any feedback, it must be considered. Overall, I decided to keep the large elements since they're easier to tap.

To conclude, I think I personally got a lot of value from this expercience. It's one thing to create a design, but it's another to start a whole project from scratch, research and all, and see it to its completion. Well, the design aspect at least. I'm glad I don't have to do the back-end.
